window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>1","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : KINETIC THEORY OF MATTER.","question":"Which of the following can be explained by the kinetic theory? I. The physical state of matter II. Diffusion of gases III. Melting of solide IV. Evaporation of liquids","images":[],"options":{"A":"IV","B":"I and II","C":"III aand IV","D":"I, II, III and IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The kinetic theory of gases explains the behavior of gases in terms of particles in motion. It can explain the physical state of matter (I), diffusion of gases (II), and the processes of melting (III) and evaporation (IV). Therefore, all four statements can be explained by the kinetic theory, making the correct option 'I, II, III and IV'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>2","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ATOMIC NUMBER/PROTON NUMBER, NUMBER OF NEUTRONS, ISOTOPES, ATOMIC MASS, MASS NUMBER.","question":"Which of the following species is/are electrically neutral?  ProtonsNeutronsElectronsI. P91010II.Q171818III.R172017IVS121212","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii and iii"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In the context of atomic structure, protons are positively charged, electrons are negatively charged, and neutrons are electrically neutral. Therefore, only species Q (17 protons, 18 neutrons, 18 electrons) and R (17 protons, 20 neutrons, 17 electrons) are electrically neutral. Thus, the correct option is 'iii and iv'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>3","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : FUNCTIONAL GROUP","question":"All members of a homologous series I. conform to a general molecular formula. II. show similar chemical properties III. can be obtained by a general method of preparation IV. have the same physical properties.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii and iii"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Members of a homologous series share a general molecular formula (I), show similar chemical properties (II), and can be obtained by a general method of preparation (III). However, they do not necessarily have the same physical properties (IV) as these can vary. Therefore, the correct option is 'i, ii and iii'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>4","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"SOLUBILITY OF SUBTANCES : GENERAL PRINCIPLES","question":"Which of the following deductions is/are correct of the diagram?    i. The solubility of R is directly proportional to tempera-ture. II. Q is insoluble in water at O0C III. A mixture of R and Q can be separated by fractional crystallization. IV. R is less soluble in hot water than in cold water.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii and iii"},"answer":"C","explanation":"III. A mixture of R and Q can be separated by fractional crystallization. IV. R is less soluble in hot water than in cold water are correct","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>5","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY, INDUSTRY AND THE ENVIRONMENT : CHEMICAL INDUSTRY","question":"The factors which should be taken into consideration when establishing a paint industry include l.energy requirements. II. disposal system for effluents. III. adequacy of water supply. IV. availability of pigments.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii,iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When establishing a paint industry, all factors listed are important: energy requirements (I), disposal system for effluents (II), adequacy of water supply (III), and availability of pigments (IV). Therefore, the correct option is 'i, ii, iii and iv'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>6","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : EXTRACTION OF METALS","question":"Which of the following can be obtained from its oxide by heating with carbon? I. Lead II. Zinc III. Iron IV. Calcium","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii and iii"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Lead (I) and Zinc (II) can be obtained from their oxides by heating with carbon, as carbon can reduce these metal oxides to their respective metals. Iron (III) can also be reduced in this manner, but Calcium (IV) cannot be obtained from its oxide by heating with carbon. Therefore, the correct option is 'i, ii and iii'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>7","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : OXIDATION AND REDUCTION PROCESS.","question":"Oxidation is a reaction which can involve I. Loss of electrons. II. increase in oxidation number. III. gain of oxygen. IV. loss of hydrogen.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii,iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Oxidation is defined as a reaction that involves the loss of electrons (I), an increase in oxidation number (II), the gain of oxygen (III), and the loss of hydrogen (IV). Therefore, all four statements are correct, making option 'i,ii,iii and iv' the correct choice.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>8","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : ELECTROLYSIS","question":"Selective discharge of ions during electrolysis depends on the I. position of ions in the electrochemical series. II. nature of the electrodes. III. charge on the ions. IV. quantity of electricity passed through the electroylyte.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii,iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The selective discharge of ions during electrolysis is influenced by the position of ions in the electrochemical series (I), the nature of the electrodes (II), the charge on the ions (III), and the quantity of electricity passed through the electrolyte (IV). All four factors are relevant, thus option 'i,ii,iii and iv' is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>9","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE","question":"Which of the following equations illustrate(s) substitution reaction?  I. 2CH_(3CH2OH + 2Na \u2192 2CH3CH2ONa + H2  II. C6H6 + HNO3 \u2192 C6H5NO2 + H2O  III. CH_(3CH2OH + HBr \u2192 CH_(3CH2Br + H2O  IV. CH4 + Cl2  \u2192 CH3Cl + HCl","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii and iii"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A substitution reaction involves the replacement of one atom or group in a molecule with another. In the provided equations, only III (CH3CH2OH + HBr \u2192 CH3CH2Br + H2O) and IV (CH4 + Cl2 \u2192 CH3Cl + HCl) illustrate substitution reactions. Therefore, the correct option is 'iii and iv'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>10","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : PROPERTIES AND USES OF ALUMINIUM AND ITS COMPOUNDS","question":"Which of the following methods is/are applicable in preventing corrosion of metals? I. storing in oil II. Allowing an inert oxide surface layer to form III. Coating with paint or tar IV. Plating with another metal","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i,ii,iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Methods to prevent corrosion include storing metals in oil (I), allowing an inert oxide surface layer to form (II), coating with paint or tar (III), and plating with another metal (IV). All these methods are effective in preventing corrosion, making option 'i,ii,iii and iv' the correct choice.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>11","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : PETROLEUM/CRUDE OIL","question":"Which of the following separation is routinely applied in the petroleum industry","images":[],"options":{"A":"Filtration","B":"Chromatography","C":"Evaporation","D":"Fractional distillation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Fractional distillation is a separation process that takes advantage of differences in boiling points of components in a mixture. In the petroleum industry, crude oil is separated into various fractions (like gasoline, kerosene, diesel, etc.) using fractional distillation, making it the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>12","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC BIOCHEMISTRY AND SYNTHETIC POLYMERS : CARBOHYDRATES","question":"Starch undergoes complete hydrolysis to produce","images":[],"options":{"A":"maltose","B":"lactose","C":"fructose","D":"glucose"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Starch is a polysaccharide that, upon complete hydrolysis, breaks down into glucose molecules. This process involves the enzymatic or acid-catalyzed breakdown of starch into its monomer units, which are glucose. Therefore, glucose is the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>13","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : DIAMOND AND GRAPHITE","question":"Which of the following solids has a network structure?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Diamond","B":"lodine","C":"Sulphur","D":"Graphite"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Diamond has a network structure where each carbon atom is tetrahedrally bonded to four other carbon atoms, forming a strong and rigid three-dimensional lattice. This structure gives diamond its exceptional hardness. Thus, diamond is the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>14","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"Trioxosulphate (lV) acid is not stored for a long period because it","images":[],"options":{"A":"is a weak dibasic acid","B":"has bleaching properties","C":"is unstable and eaily decomposed","D":"smells strongly of sulphur (lV) oxide"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Trioxosulphate (IV) acid, also known as sulfurous acid, is unstable and can decompose over time, especially when exposed to heat or light. This instability makes it unsuitable for long-term storage, which is why the option stating it is unstable and easily decomposed is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>15","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"Which of the following statements is not correct about the compound represented below?  COOH  |  COOH","images":[],"options":{"A":"Its basicity is 4","B":"It is a dicarboxylic acid","C":"its boiling point is higher than that of the corresponding alkane","D":"it reacts with alkanols under suitable condittions"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The compound represented is a dicarboxylic acid (as it has two -COOH groups). Its basicity is not 4; it is actually 2, as it can donate two protons. Therefore, the statement 'Its basicity is 4' is incorrect, making option 1 the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>16","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANES","question":"Alkanes are used mainly","images":[],"options":{"A":"in the production of plastics","B":"as domestic and industrial fuels","C":"in the textile industry","D":"in the hydrogenation of oils"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Alkanes are primarily used as fuels in both domestic and industrial applications due to their high energy content and relatively clean combustion. They are the main components of natural gas and gasoline, making this option the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>17","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : PROPERTIES AND USES OF COPPER AND ITS COMPOUNDS.","question":"Which of the following solids will leave a black residue after being heated strongly?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Iron(I) tetraoxossulphate(VI)","B":"Lead (II) trioxocarbonate (IV)","C":"Copper (II) trioxonitrate (V)","D":"Calcium trioxocarbonate(IV)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"On strong heating, copper(II) nitrate decomposes to give black copper(II) oxide (CuO), along with nitrogen dioxide and oxygen. This black residue makes it the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>18","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL BONDS : IONIC COMPOUNDS","question":"The properties of electrovalent compounds include the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"high melting point and boiling point","B":"conduction of electricity in the molten state","C":"high volatility at room temperature","D":"ionization in aqueous solution."},"answer":"C","explanation":"Electrovalent compounds, also known as ionic compounds, typically have high melting and boiling points, conduct electricity in molten state, ionize in aqueous solution, and can decompose under electric current. However, they are not characterized by high volatility at room temperature, making option 3 the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>19","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ISOMERISM","question":"Which of the following pairs illustrates isotopy?","images":[],"options":{"A":"But-l-ene and but -2-ene","B":"Ortho-hydrogen and parahydrogen","C":"Oxygen and ozone","D":"Hydrogen and deuterium"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Isotopes are variants of a particular chemical element that have the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons. Hydrogen and deuterium are both isotopes of hydrogen; hydrogen has one proton and no neutrons, while deuterium has one proton and one neutron. Therefore, the correct option is 'Hydrogen and deuterium'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>20","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANES","question":"Carbon is often deposited in the exhaust-pipe of cars because of the?","images":[],"options":{"A":"presence of carbon in petrol","B":"dehydrogenation of petrol","C":"incomplete combustion of petrol","D":"presence of additives in petrol"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Carbon is often deposited in the exhaust pipe of cars due to the incomplete combustion of petrol. When combustion is incomplete, not all carbon in the fuel is converted to carbon dioxide, leading to the formation of soot and other carbon deposits. Thus, the correct option is 'incomplete combustion of petrol'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>21","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : CONCEPT OF PH","question":"What does X atand for in the following expression? X = -Log(10)((H+)","images":[],"options":{"A":"Enthalpy change (\u2206H)","B":"Equilibrium constant (K)","C":"Solubility product","D":"Degree of acidity (pH)"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the expression X = -Log_10(H^+), X represents the degree of acidity, commonly known as pH. The pH scale measures how acidic or basic a solution is, with lower values indicating higher acidity. Therefore, the correct option is 'Degree of acidity (pH)'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>22","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : SULPHUR","question":"Sulphur burns in air to form","images":[],"options":{"A":"an acidic oxide","B":"a basic oxide","C":"an amphoteric oxide","D":"a neutral oxide"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Sulfur burns in air to form sulfur dioxide (SO2), which is an acidic oxide. Acidic oxides are oxides that react with water to form acids. Therefore, the correct option is 'an acidic oxide'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>23","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL KINETICS AND EQUILIBRIUM SYSTEM : EQUILIBRIUM","question":"In which of the following changes is \u2206S negative ?","images":[],"options":{"A":"H2O(l) \u2192 H2O(s)","B":"C(s) + 1/2O2(g) \u2192 CO(g)","C":"PCI5(g) \u2192 PCl3(g) + Cl_((2(g))","D":"NaCl(s) + aq \u2192 Na+(aq) + Cl-(aq)"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The change H2O(l) \u2192 H2O(s) represents the freezing of water, which is a process that decreases the entropy (\u2206S) of the system because the molecules are moving from a more disordered state (liquid) to a more ordered state (solid). Therefore, the correct option is 'H2O(l) \u2192 H2O(s)'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>24","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HALOGENS","question":"Chlorine is is used in water treatment as","images":[],"options":{"A":"a germicide","B":"a decolorizing agent","C":"an antioxidant","D":"a coagulating agent"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Chlorine is primarily used in water treatment as a germicide. It effectively kills bacteria and other pathogens in water, making it safe for drinking. The other options do not accurately describe the primary function of chlorine in this context.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>25","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO CHEMISTRY : SCIENTIFIC METHODS","question":"Which of the following pieces of apparatus can be used for drawing a current of air through a liquid?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Wash bottle","B":"Aspirator","C":"Capillary tube","D":"Thistle funnel"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct apparatus for drawing a current of air through a liquid is an 'Aspirator'. An aspirator works by creating a vacuum that draws air (or liquid) through a system. It typically uses water flow to create this vacuum, allowing it to pull air through a liquid, which is essential in various laboratory processes. The other options, such as a wash bottle, capillary tube, thistle funnel, and pipette, do not serve this specific function.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>26","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : ELECTROCHEMICAL CELLS","question":"What amount of copper will be deposited if a current of 10A was passed through a solution of copper(ll) salt for 965 seconds? (1F = 96500 C)","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.005 mole","B":"0.025 mole","C":"0.05 mole","D":"1.00 mole"},"answer":"C","explanation":"To calculate the amount of copper deposited, we use the formula: moles = (current in amperes \u00d7 time in seconds) / (n \u00d7 F), where n is the number of electrons transferred (for Cu, n=2). Here, moles = (10 A \u00d7 965 s) / (2 \u00d7 96500 C) = 0.05 moles. Therefore, the correct answer is 0.05 mole.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>27","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : PROPERTIES AND USES OF ALUMINIUM AND ITS COMPOUNDS","question":"Some precious stones such as ruby and sapphire consist of aluminum oxide coloured by traces of the oxides of","images":[],"options":{"A":"group lV elements","B":"group l metals","C":"transition metals","D":"alkaline earths"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ruby and sapphire are colored by traces of transition metals, such as chromium in ruby and titanium/iron in sapphire. The other groups mentioned do not typically contribute to the coloration of these gemstones.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>28","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL KINETICS AND EQUILIBRIUM SYSTEM : EQUILIBRIUM","question":"Consider the reaction represented by the following equation CaCI2(aq) + H2C2O4(aq) \u21cc CaC2O4(s) + 2HCI(aq). Which of the following would dissolve the precipitate of CaC _2O4 formed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Stirring the mixture vigorously","B":"Adding more calcium chloride solution","C":"lncreasing the concentration of the ethanedioic acid","D":"Adding concentrated hydrochloric acid"},"answer":"D","explanation":"To dissolve the precipitate of calcium oxalate (CaC2O4), adding concentrated hydrochloric acid would provide additional calcium ions and increase the solubility of the precipitate by shifting the equilibrium. The other options would not effectively dissolve the precipitate.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>29","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKENES","question":"The following gases decolorize bromine water except","images":[],"options":{"A":"C2H6","B":"C2H4","C":"C2H2","D":"C3H4"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Ethane (C2H6) does not decolorize bromine water because it is a saturated hydrocarbon and does not have double or triple bonds that can react with bromine. The other gases listed are unsaturated and can react with bromine, leading to decolorization.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>30","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE TITRATION","question":"What volume of distilled water should be added to 400cm3 of 2.0 mole dm-3 H2SO4 to obtain 0.20 mole dm-3 of solution?","images":[],"options":{"A":"600cm3","B":"800cm3","C":"1,000cm3","D":"3,600cm3"},"answer":"D","explanation":"To find the volume of distilled water to be added, we can use the dilution formula: C1V1 = C2V2, where C1 is the initial concentration (2.0 mole/dm^3), V1 is the initial volume (400 cm^3), C2 is the final concentration (0.20 mole/dm^3), and V2 is the final volume. Rearranging gives V2 = (C1V1) / C2 = (2.0 * 400) / 0.20 = 4000 cm^3. The volume of distilled water to be added is V2 - V1 = 4000 cm^3 - 400 cm^3 = 3600 cm^3. Therefore, the correct option is 3,600 cm^3.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>31","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HALOGENS","question":"Which of the following indicates the correct increasing order of oxidizing power of the halogens?","images":[],"options":{"A":"F","B":"l","C":"I","D":"Br"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The oxidizing power of halogens depends on how easily they gain electrons to form halide ions. As you move up Group 17, atoms become smaller and more electronegative, so they attract electrons more strongly.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>32","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : OXYGEN","question":"Which of the following substances is a peroxide?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Na2O2","B":"CuO","C":"PbO4","D":"Fe2O"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A peroxide is a compound that contains an oxygen-oxygen single bond (O-O). Among the given options, Na2O2 (sodium peroxide) is the only substance that fits this definition. Therefore, the correct option is Na2O2.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>33","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STOICHIOMETRY AND CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE.","question":"What volume of propane is left unreacted when 20cm3 of oxygen and 20cm3 of propane react according to the following equation? C3H8 + 5(O)2 \u2192 3CO2(g) + 4H2Og","images":[],"options":{"A":"4cm3","B":"5cm3","C":"14cm3","D":"16cm3"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The balanced equation shows that 1 mole of propane reacts with 5 moles of oxygen. Therefore, for every 1 volume of propane, 5 volumes of oxygen are required. Since 20 cm\u00b3 of propane is used with only 20 cm\u00b3 of oxygen, there is not enough oxygen to react with all the propane. The amount of propane that can react is 20 cm\u00b3 of oxygen / 5 = 4 cm\u00b3 of propane. Thus, the unreacted propane is 20 cm\u00b3 - 4 cm\u00b3 = 16 cm\u00b3.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>34","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : OXYGEN","question":"The component of air that removed when air is bubbled into alkaline pyrogallol solution is","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbon(lV) oxide","B":"oxgyen","C":"water vapour","D":"nitrogen"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When air is bubbled into alkaline pyrogallol solution, the component of air that is removed is oxygen. Pyrogallol reacts with oxygen to form a colorless solution, effectively removing oxygen from the air. Therefore, the correct option is oxygen.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>35","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STANDARD SEPARATION TECHNIQUES FOR MIXTURES : SEPARATION TECHNIQUES","question":"Which of the following will not affect the degree of hardness in a sample of temporarily hard water?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Addition of washing soda","B":"Adding of soap","C":"Treatment with carbon exchange resin","D":"Filtration"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The degree of hardness in temporarily hard water is primarily due to the presence of calcium and magnesium bicarbonates, which can be removed by boiling. The addition of washing soda, soap, or treatment with a carbon exchange resin can affect hardness. However, filtration and distillation do not affect the hardness of temporarily hard water, as they do not remove the dissolved minerals. Therefore, the correct option is filtration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>36","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC BIOCHEMISTRY AND SYNTHETIC POLYMERS : SYNTHETIC POLYMERS","question":"Examples of polymers include the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"starch","B":"nylon","C":"wool","D":"glass"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Glass is not a polymer; it is an inorganic solid made from silica and other compounds. Polymers are large molecules made up of repeating structural units (monomers), such as starch, nylon, and wool, which are organic compounds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>37","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOATES AS DRIVATIVES OF ALKANOIC ACIDS","question":"When the trioxonitrate (IV) salt of an alkali metal Y is heated, the formula of the residue is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Y2O","B":"YNO2","C":"Y2O3","D":"Y(NO2)2"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When the trioxonitrate (IV) salt of an alkali metal Y is heated, it typically decomposes to form the metal oxide (Y2O) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2). Therefore, the residue would be Y2O, which is the oxide of the alkali metal.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>38","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : OXIDIZING AND REDUCING AGENTS.","question":"Which of the following compounds of tin is a strong reducing agent?","images":[],"options":{"A":"SnCI2","B":"SnCI4","C":"SnO)2","D":"SnH4"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Tin hydride (SnH4) is a strong reducing agent because it can donate electrons easily. It is often used in organic synthesis to reduce various functional groups.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>39","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ELECTRON CONFIGURATION","question":"Which of the following ions has the same electronic structure?  [Use the following information: 147N, 168O, 199 F3115P 8035Br]","images":[],"options":{"A":"Nitride","B":"Oxide","C":"Bromide","D":"Phosphade"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The ions that have the same electronic structure are those that have the same number of electrons. Nitride (N^3-) and Fluoride (F^-) both have 10 electrons, matching the electronic structure of Neon (Ne). Therefore, the correct answer is Nitride.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>40","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : DELIQUESCENT, EFFLORESCENT AND HYGROSCOPIC COMPOUND.","question":"In which of the following pairs are both substances deliquescent?","images":[],"options":{"A":"CaCI2 and H2SO4","B":"NaOH and MgSO47H2O","C":"CaCI2 and NaOH","D":"CuO and NaCI"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Both CaCl2 (calcium chloride) and H2SO4 (sulfuric acid) are deliquescent substances, meaning they can absorb moisture from the air and dissolve in the absorbed water to form a solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>41","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HYDROGEN","question":"Producer gas is a mixture of","images":[],"options":{"A":"oxygen and hydrogen","B":"Hydrogen and nitrogen","C":"nitrogen and oxygen","D":"nitrogen and carbon (ll) oxide"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Producer gas is obtained when air is passed over red-hot coke (carbon). Since air contains oxygen and nitrogen, the oxygen reacts with carbon to form carbon(II) oxide (CO), while the nitrogen from air remains unchanged.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>42","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKENES","question":"An alkene may be converted to an alkane by","images":[],"options":{"A":"halogenation","B":"hydrolysis","C":"dehydration","D":"hydrogenation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An alkene can be converted to an alkane through hydrogenation, which involves the addition of hydrogen  across the double bond of the alkene. This process saturates the molecule, turning it into an alkane. Therefore, the correct option is hydrogenation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>43","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL BONDS : IONIC COMPOUNDS","question":"Which of the following compounds has the highest ionic character?","images":[],"options":{"A":"KCls","B":"BeCl2","C":"HClg","D":"AlCl3(s)"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The greater the electronegativity difference between the metal and chlorine, the higher the ionic character.    KCl \u2192 Potassium is a large Group 1 alkali metal with very low electronegativity. The difference between K (0.8) and Cl (3.0) is very high, making KCl highly ionic.    BeCl\u2082 and AlCl\u2083 \u2192 small, highly charged cations (Be\u00b2\u207a, Al\u00b3\u207a) cause strong polarization of Cl\u207b, giving more covalent character.    HCl \u2192 a polar covalent molecule, not ionic.    CaCl\u2082 \u2192 ionic, but calcium (1.0) has less difference with chlorine than potassium does.    Therefore, KCl(s) has the highest ionic character among the options.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>44","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HYDROGEN","question":"The following gases are diatomic except","images":[],"options":{"A":"nitrogen","B":"helium","C":"hydrogen","D":"fluorine"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Among the gases listed, helium is the only monatomic gas, while nitrogen, hydrogen, fluorine, and oxygen are all diatomic gases. Diatomic gases consist of two atoms, while monatomic gases consist of single atoms. Thus, the correct option is helium.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>45","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ORBITALS","question":"Which of the following is correct about the electrons in the 1s orbital? They","images":[],"options":{"A":"have the same spin","B":"are easier to remove than those in the 2p orbital","C":"are closest to the nucleus","D":"have the same energy as those in the 2s orbital"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Electrons in the 1s orbital are indeed closest to the nucleus compared to electrons in higher energy orbitals like 2p or 2s. This proximity results in a stronger attraction to the positively charged nucleus, making them more stable. Therefore, the correct option is that they are closest to the nucleus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>46","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC BIOCHEMISTRY AND SYNTHETIC POLYMERS : ALCOHOLS","question":"The product of the reaction between ethanol and excess acidified K2Cr2O7 is","images":[],"options":{"A":"ethanal","B":"ethylethanoate","C":"ethanoic acid","D":"ethyne"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When ethanol is oxidized by excess acidified potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7), the product formed is ethanoic acid (acetic acid). This reaction involves the conversion of the alcohol group in ethanol to a carboxylic acid group. Therefore, the correct option is ethanoic acid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>47","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"RADIAOACTIVITY","question":"What does the following eqquation illustrate?  23892U \u2192 23490Th + 42He","images":[],"options":{"A":"Nuclear fission","B":"Nuclear fusion","C":"Artificial radioactivity","D":"Spontaneous disintegration"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The equation illustrates the process of spontaneous disintegration, specifically alpha decay. In this reaction, Uranium-238 (23892U) decays into Thorium-234 (23490Th) and an alpha particle (42He). This is a natural process where an unstable nucleus loses energy by emitting radiation, resulting in the transformation of one element into another. The other options do not accurately describe this process.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>48","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"When ammonium chloride is dissolved in water in a test tube, the tube feels colder showing that","images":[],"options":{"A":"the solution is unsaturated","B":"sublimation has ocurred","C":"ammonia gas is evolved","D":"the process is endothermic"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When ammonium chloride (NH4Cl) is dissolved in water, the process absorbs heat from the surroundings, resulting in a temperature drop that makes the test tube feel colder. This indicates that the dissolution process is endothermic, meaning it requires heat from the environment. Therefore, the correct option is that the process is endothermic.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>49","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : REACTIVITY OF IRON AND ALUMINIUM WITH AIR, WATER AND ACIDS","question":"Zinc displaces copper from an aqueous solution of copper (ll) salt because","images":[],"options":{"A":"copper is a transition element","B":"copper is a moderately reactive metal","C":"Zinc and copper have reducing properties","D":"zinc is more reactive than copper"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Zinc displaces copper from an aqueous solution of copper (II) salt because zinc is more reactive than copper. This is based on the reactivity series of metals, which ranks metals according to their ability to displace other metals from solutions of their ions. Since zinc is higher in the reactivity series than copper, it can displace copper ions from the solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1993>50","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1993","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : ALLOYS","question":"The alloy used for metal work and plumbing contains","images":[],"options":{"A":"lead and tin","B":"iron and carbon","C":"copper and tin","D":"aluminium and copper"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The alloy used for metal work and plumbing is typically bronze, which is an alloy of copper and tin. This combination provides desirable properties such as corrosion resistance and strength, making it suitable for various applications in plumbing and metal work.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];